"1370","Beckington, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived on or by a hill, from Middle English <i>hill</i>, <i>hell</i>, <i>hull</i> ‘hill’ (Old English <i>hyll</i>). Compare   Hiller  . This surname is also very common among African Americans.","English: possibly in some cases from the personal name <i>Hille</i>, a pet form of some name such as   Hilger   or   Hillary  .","German: from a short form of   Hildebrand   or any of a variety of other names, male and female, containing ancient Germanic <i>hild</i> ‘battle’ as the first element."],"variants":[{"name":"Hillock","meanings":["English and Scottish: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(by the) small hill’, from Middle English <i>hillok</i>, a diminutive of <i>hille</i> (Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’). See   Hill  ."]},{"name":"Hills","meanings":["English: variant of   Hill   with genitival <i>-s</i> if a relationship name, attested in Matilda <i>Hilles</i>, 1327 (Somerset), where the genitival form may signify widowhood; or with plural <i>-s</i> if habitational, attested in Johanne <i>de Hyles</i>, 1379 (Bickerstaffe, Lancashire), and Ricardo <i>del Hyles</i>, 1379 (Great Eccleston, Lancashire); or, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, probably the most common form."]},{"name":"Hiller","meanings":["German: metronymic from <i>Hille</i>, a pet form of the female personal name <i>Hildegund</i> (see   Hilke  ).","German: from a masculine personal beginning with the ancient Germanic element <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’.","German: variant of <b>Hüller</b> (see   Huller  )."]},{"name":"Hil","meanings":["Altered form of English   Hill  .","Dutch (<b>Van den Hil</b>): topographic name from <i>hil, hul</i> ‘hill’, particularly in the sense of a <i>flight hill</i> above sea level in the southwestern Netherlands."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Hill was born in 1345, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Thomas Brooke."},"et":{"1345–":"1345–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1345":"1345","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","Beckington, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1345–":"1345–Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","1345–Female":"1345–Kuollut","134